2nd exercise: Data summary and regression analysis basics

The exercise consist 5 parts, which are separated in own sections (below). Data for the exercise was read from http://www.helsinki.fi/~kvehkala/JYTmooc/JYTOPKYS3-data.txt and it was processed (data wrangling) using a R script (create_learning2014.R). Data is stored into /data/learning2014.csv file. I wonât go into details about the data wrangling, so look at the file if interested.

Scripts can be found from my /scripts folder in IODS-projectâs github repository.

1st part

First things first, so letâs read the data

learning_data <- read.table("data/learning2014.csv",sep=",",header=T)

Data in this exercise is sample of bigger student questionnaire. It has 7 variables and 166 observations and the structure is following:

## 'data.frame':    166 obs. of  7 variables:

Questionnaire is about different kind of studying orientations. Orientation approaches were deep, surface (surf) and strategic (stra) approached orientations. In addition, gender, age, points and attitude were recorded from the students.

Letâs assume that total points is linear combinations of those variables and errors are normally distributed, not correlated and have constant variance, \(\sigma^2\). 5th part

Diagnostic plots are following for my first model with attitude, age and strategic approach variables.

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(my_model2, which = c(1,2,5))

interpretation:

  • From the Q-Q plot supports assumption that the errors of the model are normally distributed (or it was reasonable).

  • Residual plot does not show any clear patterns, so I probably can assume that the errors have constant variance (more or less random scatter plot).

  • It seems that no observations in our dataset that has high leverage on our fit.

3rd exercise: Data summary and predictin alcohol consumption

1st and 2nd part of the exercise

Data for the exercise was read from https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Student+Performance and it was processed (data wrangling) using a R script (create_alc.R). Data is stored into /data/student_acl.csv file. I wonât go into details about the data wrangling, so look at the file if you are interested.

Data is very well described in the student.txt file which came with the data. Please refer to link to original data repository (above). Briefly, data is about secondary schoolâs studentâ alcohol consumption. Data used in this exercise was combined from two different, but identical surveys which was given to math course and Portuguese course students. We are interested about alcohol users, who use regularly it. New variable, high_use was created and was true for those students who used alcohol more than two times per week, others was set false.

Scripts can be (again) found in my /scripts folder in IODS-projectâs github repository.
